0.body: Moosync lets you create your own extensions to extent the functionality for the main app. Extensions are web-assembly modules that can be loaded at runtime.
0.title: Introduction

1.body: Web assembly is platform independant and has a few restrictions: Limited access to the file system Limited access to the network No support for threads (tracking wasi-threads ) No support for native libraries
1.title: Restrictions

2.body: Moosync uses extism under the hood to load web assembly modules. Any host language supported by extism can be used to write extensions. Currently we only provide support for Rust Javascript / Typescript Python

9.body:
The extension development kit provides APIs to fetch data from the main app. For this example lets consider the getCurrentSong API. getCurrentSong returns the actively playling song. Rust
Python
Javascript impl Provider for SampleExtension { fn get_provider_scopes(&self) -> Result<Vec<ExtensionProviderScope>> { Ok(vec![ExtensionProviderScope::Scrobble]) } fn scrobble(&self, song: Song) -> Result<()> { let song: Option<Song> = moosync_edk::api::extension_api::get_current_song()?; Ok(()) } } class SampleExtension(Extension): def __init__(self): super().__init__() def get_provider_scopes(self) -> List[ProviderScopes]: return ["scrobble"] def scrobble(self, song: Song): song: Optional[Song] = self.api.get_current_song() return import { api } from '@moosync/edk' export function entry() { api.on('getProviderScopes', () => { return ['scrobble'] }); api.on('onScrobble', async (term) => { const song = await api.getCurrentSong(); return })
}
